      <hedline>
        <hl1>Which Burner?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Fred Levy letter notes there was no mention in July 30 article on plight of Campbell Soup Co of improving sales by making better soup (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It was only after I put down the paper and went into the kitchen for a little lunch that I realized something about your article on the destiny of the Campbell Soup Company (''The First Family of Soup, Feeling the Squeeze,'' July 30).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It was only after I put down the paper and went into the kitchen for a little lunch that I realized something about your article on the destiny of the Campbell Soup Company (''The First Family of Soup, Feeling the Squeeze,'' July 30).</p>
        <p>Matters dynastic, corporate, executive, financial, promotional, sociological, historical, genealogical -- even equestrian -- filled the pages. Yet among the multifarious ideas for bolstering the company's fortunes, little mention was made of a traditional way of improving sales -- make better soup.</p>
        <p>FRED LEVY  La Selva Beach, Calif., July 31</p>
      </block>
